<subSubSection lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="149" pageId="11" pageNumber="148" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,1915,2013]" lastBlockId="12.[151,1436,151,285]" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="149" pageId="11" pageNumber="148">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,260,1915,1941]" pageId="11" pageNumber="148">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Grant, R." box="[274,420,1915,1941]" pageId="11" pageNumber="148" pagination="1 - 56" refId="ref9113" refString="Grant, R. (1976) The marine fauna of New Zealand: Isididae (Octocorallia: Gorgonacea) from New Zealand and the Antarctic. New Zealand Oceanographic Institute Memoir, 66, 1 - 56." type="journal article" year="1976">Grant (1976)</bibRefCitation>
attributed this species to the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1883" box="[822,923,1915,1941]" class="Anthozoa" family="Isididae" genus="Lepidisis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="11" pageNumber="148" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[822,923,1915,1941]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="148">Lepidisis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on the basis of the polyp body being covered with scales, a feature that he accepted as defining the genus. 
<bibRefCitation author="Watling, L. &amp; France, S. C." box="[846,1134,1951,1977]" pageId="11" pageNumber="148" pagination="97 - 110" refId="ref9486" refString="Watling, L. &amp; France, S. C. (2021) Towards a revision of the bamboo corals: Part 2, untangling the genus Lepidisis (Octocorallia: Isididae). Bulletin of the Peabody Museum of Natural History, 62, 97 - 110. https: // doi. org / 10.3374 / 014.062.0202" type="journal article" year="2021">
Watling &amp; 
<collectingCountry box="[973,1049,1951,1977]" name="France" pageId="11" pageNumber="148">France</collectingCountry>
(2021)
</bibRefCitation>
, however, showed that the original diagnosis of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1883" box="[500,601,1987,2013]" class="Anthozoa" family="Isididae" genus="Lepidisis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="11" pageNumber="148" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[500,601,1987,2013]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="148">Lepidisis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as having the polyp body covered in scales was in error and that most species assigned to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1883" box="[335,436,151,177]" class="Anthozoa" family="Isididae" genus="Lepidisis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="12" pageNumber="149" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[335,436,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="149">Lepidisis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
needed to be reassigned to other genera. While the polyp morphology of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Grant" authorityYear="1976" box="[1266,1391,151,177]" class="Anthozoa" family="Isididae" genus="Lepidisis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="12" pageNumber="149" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="solitaria">
<emphasis box="[1266,1391,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="149">L. solitaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has not been re-examined in detail, genetic data shows the 
<typeStatus box="[768,816,187,213]" pageId="12" pageNumber="149">type</typeStatus>
specimen to be nested within the clade H1, sister to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Watling et al. 2022)" baseAuthorityName="Watling" baseAuthorityYear="2022" class="Anthozoa" family="Isididae" genus="Keratoisis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="12" pageNumber="149" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="magnifica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="149">O. magnifica</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Watling, L. &amp; Heestand Saucier, E. &amp; France, S. C." box="[278,499,223,249]" pageId="12" pageNumber="149" pagination="337 - 375" refId="ref9546" refString="Watling, L. Heestand Saucier, E. &amp; France, S. C. (2022) Towards a revision of the bamboo corals: Part 4, delineating the family Keratoisididae. Zootaxa, 5093 (3), 337 - 375. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 5093.3.4" type="journal article" year="2022">Watling et al. 2022</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. The covering of the proximal half or so of the polyp body in a layer of scales can be seen in 
<figureCitation box="[270,414,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1155,1179]" captionTargetBox="[151,1433,309,1122]" captionTargetId="figure-94@12.[151,1435,309,1132]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 11. Onkoisis magnifica, specimen K3830, A, view of preserved polyps, B, piece of external tunic with embedded sclerites, C, light microscope image of tunic and calcareous nodules. Onkoisis solitaria, D, E, individual polyps, with surface and transmitted illumination showing scale sclerites on lower portion of polyp body." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6877197" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6877197/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="149">Figs. 11D, E</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
